tica'' (iiO album)]]\n*''[[Poetica (All Beauty Sleeps)]]'', a 2013 album by Sopor \u00c6ternus & the Ensemble of Shadows\n\n==Typeface==\n*[[Poetica (typeface)]]\n\n{{disambiguation}}\n", "text_old": "'''Poetica''' may refer to:\n\nThe penname of lesser-known poet and creative writer Danielle A. Hossain, previously known as Danielle A. Parker and Danielle A. Galvan.\n\n==Books==\n*[[Poetics (Aristotle)|''Poetics'' (Aristotle)]]\n*''Poetica'', a work by [[Girolamo Muzio]]\n\n==Music==\n*[[Poetica Bey]] Moorish American Spoken Word Specialist & Recording Artist\nFrom the early 1990\u2019s known for her affiliation with Hip-Hop Band, The Roots as a member of the \nThen artist collective, Foreign Objects/ Illadelph Allstars Credited for introducing Jill Scott to Tarik Trotter. Poetica is also a singer songwriter with writers publishers credit on Album release \u2018By Design\u2019 by Grand Agent. She is a voiceover artist featured in herbal essence shampoo ads, radio personality, Television host of Brooklyn Based Cable television show; Goddess Mobile TV. She is also known as \u2018your artist favorite artist, with greats, Norman Connors, Freedom Williams, John Legend amongst her list of fans. Poetica Bey is also an original founding member of the spoken word trio; Black Ice whose name is assumed by Lamar mason and titled was used to drum up fan fair for a Russell Simmons, Def Poetry as the words of \u201cBlack Ice\u2019 written by Poetica won the ensemble an Emmy award for Def Poetry on Broadway. Poetica received a citation from the city of Philadelphia\u2019s council man at large for her contribution to jazz in the city. Poetica Bey is known as a muse and for the works of community building, Missionary works of food clothing and shelter, uplifting fallen humanity and social change thru sound, collaborating with Netherlands artist Jeanne van heswijk and the Philadelphia museum of art to bring Sovereign Sound Socials and sustainability in the city with her \u2018farm to 